doc.ContractDescription: ACCESSING AND INTERPRETING THE STRUCTURE OF IMPACT CRATERS BELOW GROUND LEVEL ARE DIFFICULT TASKS EVEN ON THE EARTH. MOST INSIGHTS INTO THE SUBSURFACE STRUCTURE OF TERRESTRIAL CRATERS HAVE COME FROM INDIRECT MEANS (GRAVITY, SEISMIC, AND MAGNETOTELLURIC SURVEYS) OR LIMITED DIRECT METHODS SUCH AS DRILL CORES, ROAD AND/OR RIVER CUTS, AND FROM IMPACT STRUCTURES THAT HAVE BEEN DEEPLY SCOURED AND EXPOSED BY GLACIAL OR OTHER EROSION. ON MARS, WE HAVE IDENTIFIED A POPULATION OF CUT CRATERS THAT HAVE BEEN FORTUITOUSLY EXPOSED IN CROSS-SECTION BY A COMBINATION OF TECTONIC ACTIVITY AND EROSION. MANY OF THESE CUT CRATERS LIE ALONG THE WALLS OF THE VALLES MARINERIS TROUGH SYSTEM, WHICH STRETCHES OVER 4000 KM IN LENGTH AND HAS A VERTICAL RELIEF THAT EXCEEDS 9 KM IN PLACES. THESE CUT CRATERS PROVIDE UNIQUE OPPORTUNITIES TO DIRECTLY OBSERVE CRATER SUBSURFACE STRUCTURE IN A MANNER NOT POSSIBLE EVEN ON THE EARTH, AND THEY ARE THE FOCUS OF THIS PROPOSED RESEARCH. HERE WE PROPOSE TO CONSTRUCT HIGH-RESOLUTION, STEREO-DERIVED DIGITAL ELEVATION MODELS DEMS OF NUMEROUS CUT CRATERS IN EASTERN VALLES MARINERIS THAT OCCUR ON THE WALLS OF COPRATES CHASMA CAPRI CHASMA, AND GANGES CHASMA. NEW TOPOGRAPHIC DATA OF THESE CRATERS WILL PERMIT US TO MAP AND ANALYZE PREVIOUSLY INACCESSIBLE CRATER STRUCTURAL ELEMENTS. THESE CRATERS RANGE IN DIAMETER FROM 3.5 TO 20.7 KM, AND THEREFORE INCLUDE EXAMPLES FROM TWO MORPHOLOGIC SUBDIVISIONS OF IMPACT STRUCTURES SIMPLE CRATERS AND COMPLEX CRATERS. IN-DEPTH ANALYSES OF THESE MARTIAN CUT CRATERS WILL ALLOW US TO ADDRESS SEVERAL BROAD SCIENTIFIC THEMES AS DETAILED IN THE PROPOSAL, AND WILL ADVANCE OUR UNDERSTANDING OF CRATER FORMATION AND MODIFICATION ON MARS AND IMPACT PROCESSES IN GENERAL.
